For {= instrument_or_event =}+ NSW heavy-vehicle access instruments or official network-change events, supply {= url =}+ official public URL per instrument/event that independently supports the source-backed dossier row.

The unit is the official instrument or event: a notice, declaration, exemption, stated-map or network amendment/suspension, emergency or closure-related instrument, or comparable official access-change event. When a public C-number, notice number, declaration number, or other stable official identifier is available, put that identifier first in the `instrument_or_event` value along with the human-readable title so distinct numbered instruments stay distinguishable. Do not submit the same C-number or stable official notice identifier again under URL, title, "latest", details, PDF/download, operator-guide, or NHVR-index wording variants. The dossier should report the official source publisher, stable identifier where public, vehicle family or scheme, affected access object, relevant dates/status, source-backed effect, any genuine source dependency, limitation, missing/conflict state, or instrument-specific lifecycle relationship, and a checked date. Keep the wording factual: what the source says, not whether a vehicle may travel, whether a route is safe, how to apply for a permit, or whether an operator is compliant.

Sources should be primary official public sources for the instrument/event. Federal Register pages or official downloads, NHVR NSW state-notice entries, NHVR access-network-change notices, NHVR emergency or closure-event pages, Transport for NSW / NSW government notice sources, and official road-manager notice pages are natural fits when they publish, register, index, or directly announce the specific instrument/event. A broad official index, hub, list, table, or multi-entry PDF can count as the cited dossier URL only when the row-specific entry, section, table row, or list item, together with the headings that directly apply to it, locally exposes the instrument/event identity and enough source-backed scope/effect, temporal/status, and claimed dependency/limitation facts for that row. A title-only link, document-wide introduction, table header, route-planner context page, or general official hub is not enough by itself; if the row relies on facts that are only available on a linked dedicated notice, instrument text, download, map, or guide, cite that dedicated source instead or keep those facts out of the row. Generic official context pages, route-planner landing pages, map apps, operator guides, Service NSW journey-planning pages, general road-manager pages, news, private operator pages, unaffiliated route-planning advice, forum posts, and bare map searches do not count on their own unless the cited URL itself directly names or links the specific instrument/event and supports the row's source-backed facts.

A checked date is required as a freshness note; it can be the date on which the source was checked rather than a date printed by the page.

Requirements:
- The page must communicate primary official public-source authority for the claimed instrument/event.
- The page must identify the claimed instrument/event through a stable identifier, title, notice number, C-number, stated-map/network-change notice, replacement relation, or direct official event/source-dependency link; use the public stable identifier in the submitted `instrument_or_event` value when the source exposes one.
- The page must support the reported heavy-vehicle access scope and source-backed effect: vehicle family or scheme, affected road/route/network/stated map/corridor/area/precinct/closure/detour, and what the official source says is authorised, exempted, declared, amended, suspended, conditioned, replaced, or otherwise changed.
- The page must support the reported temporal/status state through relevant dates or lifecycle wording: registration, publication, commencement, expiry, version, notice year/number, in-force/expired/future status, revocation, replacement, supersession, emergency/closure period, update date, or a clear source-backed "unclear/missing" state.
- The row must handle source dependencies and limitations conservatively: report only genuine source dependencies, source limitations, missing/conflict states, or instrument-specific replacement, revocation, supersession, source-limit, or dependency relationships supported by the cited official source. Ordinary expiry or current-status evidence is temporal/status evidence; it should not be treated as a source dependency or limitation unless the source explicitly states a replacement, revocation, supersession, source-text limit, delegated guide/map/list, or comparable relationship.
